# Core contract (read first, obey unconditionally)

Treat these rules as a **hard contract**, not advice.

## Who counts as an agent — read first

Every invocation of these rules is a complete agent run. Whether you are the top-level agent in a Cursor chat **or a sub-agent spawned via the Task tool**, you execute **all** applicable rules over your own scope of work, as if you were an independent agent. There is no "sub-agent shortcut".

Your **round** ends when you return to your caller (sub-agent → parent; top-level → user). At that moment you MUST have:

1. Declared `MODE: ...` in your plan.
2. Run pre-push hygiene per `docs-sync-before-finish.mdc` over the files you touched — yes, even if you are not pushing (the parent needs your hygiene + change-impact report to verify before it pushes for you).
3. Listed the user-visible identifiers your work touched and run the change-impact grep sweep over them (`docs-sync-before-finish.mdc` §4).
4. Output a verbatim Done check in your final / return message.

The only thing your **scenario** (below) gates is whether you commit/push, write `CHANGELOG.md`, and watch CI. Everything else applies to every agent.

## Mode detection (declare exactly once per task, before any state-mutating tool call)

Write one of `MODE: Cloud` / `MODE: Local` / `MODE: ambiguous — blocking` into your plan.

`MODE: Cloud` if **any** of: (a) system prompt contains a `<cloud_task_instructions>` block or `running as a CLOUD AGENT`; (b) `uname -s` = `Linux` **and** `pwd` starts with `/workspace` or `/home/ubuntu/`; (c) `CI=true` **or** `.cursor/cloud-agent-marker` exists at repo root.

`MODE: Local` only if no Cloud signal fires and the working tree is in a typical dev-home (`C:\Users\...`, `/Users/...`, `/home/<dev>/...` with no `/workspace` prefix).

Mixed signals (e.g. WSL: Linux uname but dev-home cwd) → `MODE: ambiguous — blocking`. **Stop and ask the user**; never default to Local.

## "Project documentation" — what this term means

**The project's documentation** = every `**/*.md` and `**/*.txt` the project itself ships, scoped per `docs-sync-before-finish.mdc`. **Discover** these files by walking the repo; do not assume any specific filename. The only file this pack pins by name is `CHANGELOG.md` (per `versioning-and-changelog.mdc`). When multiple docs disagree on the same topic, prefer the one closer to the project root and to the user-facing surface.

## You MUST

1. **Output the Done check verbatim** before you (a) tell the user the task is done, (b) open/update a PR, or (c) return to a parent agent. Each item marked `done` / `N/A: <reason>` / `blocked: <reason>`.
2. **Resolve conflicts** between code, docs, tests, CI in this order — never silently diverge: (1) product truth in **the project's documentation** (incl. `CHANGELOG.md`; discover by walking, don't assume names); (2) explicit user messages in this conversation; (3) implementation code (update code **or** docs deliberately, in the same change set); (4) CI/workflow YAML (must reflect 1+3).
3. **Execute the work yourself**; never claim a step was done without doing it.

## You MUST NOT

- Mark a task done while any Done-check item is unmet — report the blocker.
- Claim a rule "doesn't apply" without naming the concrete trigger that fails.
- Silently skip a rule — name the rule and reason if you skip.
- Weaken docs/tests/UI strings to greenwash CI; fix the implementation or update the doc in the same change set.

## Sub-agent commit/push scenarios

The "Who counts as an agent" section above is the contract for **all** agents. The scenario you fall into only gates commit/push and CI/CHANGELOG ownership:

- **Scenario A** — isolated worktree (type `best-of-n-runner`, or `git rev-parse --git-dir` differs from parent's). MAY commit and push its own branch; if it does, it also writes a `CHANGELOG.md` entry per `versioning-and-changelog.mdc`, watches CI to a documented end state per `post-push-ci-green.mdc`, and reports run IDs in its return. If the environment cannot do all of that (no `gh`, time/turn budget, missing tools), MUST NOT push — leave changes for the parent or return `blocked: <reason>`.
- **Scenario B** — shared workspace (default for `generalPurpose`, `explore`, etc.). MUST NOT `git add` / `git commit` / `git push`. Leaves modifications in the working tree. Top-level agent commits, pushes, writes the unified `CHANGELOG.md` entry covering all sub-agent changes, and watches CI.

If unsure, treat as Scenario B. **Either way, the four "Who counts as an agent" obligations still apply** — Scenario B doesn't exempt you from MODE / hygiene / grep sweep / Done check.

### Parent verification when a sub-agent returns — MUST

Before declaring your own task done, for every returned sub-agent verify:

1. **Done check** present, every item `done` or `N/A`. Any `blocked` propagates up.
2. **MODE declared** in the sub-agent's reply.
3. **Hygiene + change-impact grep sweep** reports present (per-file enumeration, identifiers-touched list). A bare aggregate count is not acceptable.
4. **CI status** (Scenario A only): sub-agent's branch reached success or a documented stop. If absent → `blocked: sub-agent did not watch CI`; watch CI yourself.
5. **CHANGELOG** (Scenario A only, if files changed): entry present. If absent → `blocked: sub-agent did not update CHANGELOG`; write the entry, push, watch CI again.

Any item missing → treat as `blocked: sub-agent did not run full agent loop`. **Do not silently re-run for the sub-agent.** Either escalate to the user, or fix it forward and consider whether the sub-agent type is suitable for this kind of task.

## Done check (output this list at end of every task / before returning)

```
[ ] MODE declared (Local | Cloud | ambiguous)
[ ] Code/build matches user intent; available tests pass
[ ] Docs review per docs-sync-before-finish.mdc — per-file enumeration (every project .md/.txt with edited / checked: ok / skipped: <reason>; aggregate counts forbidden)
[ ] .gitignore reviewed (no stray secrets, build outputs, transient logs)
[ ] Identifiers-touched listed + change-impact grep sweep clean (OR intentional carryovers OR N/A: no user-visible identifier touched)
[ ] EXE packaging satisfied (or N/A: <reason>)
[ ] .cursor/ tracked (only if commit/push happened)
[ ] CHANGELOG.md entry + version bump (only if files changed AND you push; Scenario B sub-agents: N/A — parent writes)
[ ] Local auto-push satisfied (or N/A: not Local, or no marker file)
[ ] CI watched and green (only if a push happened by you)
```

Any `blocked` → stop, report.

